@andmarti1424  I did two of things:


Tried linking with luajit, and testing if it works. Yes, it needs one change though, which works with lua-5.1 too, and was probably a good idea to have in first place. The name luaL_reg was deprecated in Lua 5.1 (src: here), it should always have been luaL_Reg. Without this luajit, and future versions of Lua fail to compile. This needs updating one line in lua.c.


Tried linking with lua-5.4, it fails to compile because luaL_register was removed. src-1 mentions a new recipe using; src-2 mentions a compatible way of migrating (look at the bottom of page) , src-3 gives a complete higher level list for migration (you might not need this). I know this one from using my own lua modules in LuaTeX: the end of the .lua module files always return a table, and the sourcing lua file stores that table in a local variable, this way a module ideally doesn't add anything to global name space (not even "name" of module, as the sourcing file uses local variable name). So, I think this will be a breaking change. Somehow the new lua files will receive a table of functions that they can assign to a local variable named sc, the rest of the file won't need any change. I think this will remain backwards compatible with luajit (which btw is not worth loosing, luajit way faster and can approach C speed for loopy arithmetic calculations). Check where luajit stands: https://julialang.org/benchmarks/. Ideally, sc-im will try to first link to luajit: pkg-config --exists luajit...

